Purpose: Add provider-level no-show patterns note to the architecture companion

[49m[39m  608, 608[0m:[39m[49m **Subgroup monitoring is not optional.** The model will perform differently across subgroups. That is a matter of fact, not hypothesis. The dashboard that surfaces subgroup AUC, subgroup intervention rates, and subgroup outcome improvement is part of the minimum viable deployment, not a post-launch enhancement. If your organization captures race/ethnicity and preferred language, include them in the dashboard. If not, include age bands, insurance type, and clinic location as proxy subgroups; these don't fully cover the concern but they're better than nothing.
[0m[49m[39m  609, 609[0m:[39m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      610[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Provider-level patterns deserve their own dashboard view.** If the model consistently flags one provider's panel as high risk, the problem may not be the patients. It may be scheduling practices: always booking new patients into early-morning slots, over-reliance on long lead times, or inflexible visit durations that push patients toward no-showing rather than calling to reschedule. A provider-level summary (aggregate no-show rate, average risk score, intervention rate, and outcome improvement) is a useful companion to the patient-level model. It helps operations teams distinguish "these patients are hard to reach" from "this provider's scheduling template doesn't match their patient population." Treat this as a standard QuickSight view grouped by `provider_id`, refreshed alongside the subgroup dashboard.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+      611[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[39m  610, 612[0m:[39m[49m **Intervention effect measurement is a separate analysis problem.**
